00:02:36.530 --> 00:02:37.830
&gt;&gt; Mark Sweeney: Good
morning, everyone.

00:02:37.830 --> 00:02:39.800
Thank you, Paulette.

00:02:39.800 --> 00:02:42.030
Members of Congress,
ladies and gentlemen,

00:02:42.030 --> 00:02:45.300
on behalf of the Librarian
of Congress Dr. Carla Hayden,

00:02:45.300 --> 00:02:47.750
it's my pleasure to
welcome to you GIS Day

00:02:47.750 --> 00:02:50.430
at the Library of Congress.

00:02:50.430 --> 00:02:53.600
Today's activities underscore
the increasing importance

00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:58.110
of geospatial data to the
formulation of public policy

00:02:58.110 --> 00:03:01.270
and execution of
legislative research.

00:03:01.270 --> 00:03:03.850
They're also point indicative
of the dramatic changes

00:03:03.850 --> 00:03:05.670
that are occurring
with geospatial data

00:03:05.670 --> 00:03:10.710
and the whole field of
geographic information sciences.

00:03:10.710 --> 00:03:14.510
Indeed, it is amazing to see
just how much policymakers,

00:03:14.510 --> 00:03:19.840
academics, analysts are now
routinely using geospatial data

00:03:19.840 --> 00:03:23.700
to make sense of our
increasingly complex world.

00:03:23.700 --> 00:03:26.530
This is a change of significant
proportions, and I'm proud

00:03:26.530 --> 00:03:27.830
to say that the Library

00:03:27.830 --> 00:03:30.470
of Congress is right there
playing an active role.

00:03:30.470 --> 00:03:34.570
A prime example of this is
our new platform called the

00:03:34.570 --> 00:03:38.830
Geospatial Hosting
Environment, GHE for short.

00:03:38.830 --> 00:03:41.290
It consists of a
series of data portals

00:03:41.290 --> 00:03:43.900
and software packages
designed to help Congress,

00:03:43.900 --> 00:03:46.060
the Congressional
Research Service,

00:03:46.060 --> 00:03:49.320
and members of the
public access, understand,

00:03:49.320 --> 00:03:52.660
and use the library's
outstanding collection of modern

00:03:52.660 --> 00:03:56.640
and historic geospatial data.

00:03:56.640 --> 00:03:59.980
I know you'll be hearing a lot
more about that later on today,

00:03:59.980 --> 00:04:02.450
especially in the afternoon.

00:04:02.450 --> 00:04:03.750
And now it is my honor

00:04:03.750 --> 00:04:05.910
to introduce this
morning's keynote speaker,

00:04:05.910 --> 00:04:08.390
United States Representative
Mark Takano,

00:04:08.390 --> 00:04:13.060
who represents California's
41st District.

00:04:13.060 --> 00:04:17.170
He represents the people of
Riverside, Moreno Valley,

00:04:17.170 --> 00:04:20.050
Jurupa Valley, and Paris.

00:04:20.050 --> 00:04:22.660
He serves as vice-ranking
member of the House Committee

00:04:22.660 --> 00:04:26.130
on Veterans Affairs and is
a member of the Education

00:04:26.130 --> 00:04:29.460
and Workforce Committee
and the Science, Space,

00:04:29.460 --> 00:04:32.010
and Technology Committee.

00:04:32.010 --> 00:04:35.880
It is highly noteworthy that
immediately after he was elected

00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:40.420
to the House in 2013,
Representative Takano

00:04:40.420 --> 00:04:42.290
and his staff enthusiastically

00:04:42.290 --> 00:04:46.290
and effectively used geospatial
data in connection with a number

00:04:46.290 --> 00:04:50.110
of creative policy studies.

00:04:50.110 --> 00:04:53.350
One of them, which was
particularly ground-breaking,

00:04:53.350 --> 00:04:56.710
used GIS data to compare
how high school funding

00:04:56.710 --> 00:05:00.640
and household income relate
to academic performance.

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:03.200
I'm delighted that we are now
going to have the opportunity

00:05:03.200 --> 00:05:06.310
to hear about some of the way
the Congressman's office has

00:05:06.310 --> 00:05:11.060
seized upon the opportunities
of GIS data in its work.

00:05:11.060 --> 00:05:14.190
So please join me in welcoming
Representative Mark Takano

00:05:14.190 --> 00:05:15.590
to the podium this morning.

00:05:15.590 --> 00:05:17.390
Thank you.

