the GIS software.

00:05:55.110 --> 00:05:59.610
Well, on December
17th, 1903, Orville

00:05:59.610 --> 00:06:01.290
and Wilbur Wright
achieved something

00:06:01.290 --> 00:06:04.590
that no one thought
possible when Orville climbed

00:06:04.590 --> 00:06:08.920
into the cockpit of a plane and
took flight for the first time

00:06:08.920 --> 00:06:12.340
with Wilbur running
alongside him.

00:06:12.340 --> 00:06:17.130
And on February 23rd, 1945,
just months before the end

00:06:17.130 --> 00:06:21.390
of World War II, six United
States Marines raised an

00:06:21.390 --> 00:06:25.900
American flag during the fierce
and tragic five-week battle

00:06:25.900 --> 00:06:30.740
of Iwojima, symbolizing the
valor of those who fought

00:06:30.740 --> 00:06:35.370
and conquered a fascist regime.

00:06:35.370 --> 00:06:37.880
And on December 24th,

00:06:37.880 --> 00:06:43.580
1968 astronaut Bill
Anders pointed his camera

00:06:43.580 --> 00:06:50.110
out of the window of Apollo 8
and captured the Earth rising

00:06:50.110 --> 00:06:52.480
above the moon, putting
our planet and all

00:06:52.480 --> 00:06:55.660
of its inhabitants into
a whole new context.

00:06:55.660 --> 00:06:58.370
But what connects
these three moments

00:06:58.370 --> 00:07:00.850
and many others throughout
our history is

00:07:00.850 --> 00:07:05.550
that we only know their glory,
understand their intensity,

00:07:05.550 --> 00:07:06.850
and appreciate their beauty

00:07:06.850 --> 00:07:10.670
because they were
captured in visual images.

00:07:10.670 --> 00:07:14.540
The power of visual images
to communicate ideas is

00:07:14.540 --> 00:07:17.090
so well accepted
that it's now cliche.

00:07:17.090 --> 00:07:19.290
A picture is worth -- well,

00:07:19.290 --> 00:07:22.200
I was going to say a
million words [inaudible].

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:26.130
But it does not diminish the
influence of that imagery --

00:07:26.130 --> 00:07:27.980
it does not -- the fact

00:07:27.980 --> 00:07:30.690
that it's a cliche does
not diminish the influence

00:07:30.690 --> 00:07:33.460
that the images has
on our ability to see

00:07:33.460 --> 00:07:36.410
and believe the truth
about our world.

00:07:36.410 --> 00:07:38.980
Now, no one will mistake
the maps we create

00:07:38.980 --> 00:07:43.260
through GIS software for iconic
photographs, but the power

00:07:43.260 --> 00:07:47.680
of images to help people see and
believe the truth still applies.

00:07:47.680 --> 00:07:51.070
And in a time when truth can be
hard to come by and even harder

00:07:51.070 --> 00:07:53.400
to communicate, there has
never been a greater need

00:07:53.400 --> 00:07:56.320
for technology that can
present information in the ways

00:07:56.320 --> 00:07:59.100
that persuade us and inspire us.

00:07:59.100 --> 00:08:02.840
And that is what first
led me and my office

00:08:02.840 --> 00:08:05.590
to start using GIS
mapping software.

00:08:05.590 --> 00:08:10.260
And it's why we continue
to use this software today.

00:08:10.260 --> 00:08:13.070
In my first term in office
I wanted to connect with

00:08:13.070 --> 00:08:15.400
and better understand
the business community

00:08:15.400 --> 00:08:16.910
in my district.

00:08:16.910 --> 00:08:20.060
And I wanted the business
community to see and understand

00:08:20.060 --> 00:08:23.430
that I was serious
about supporting them.

00:08:23.430 --> 00:08:25.590
So my office set
up a listening tour

00:08:25.590 --> 00:08:29.900
that we ambitiously called
100 Businesses in 100 Days.

00:08:29.900 --> 00:08:31.220
We didn't quite do
it in 100 days,

00:08:31.220 --> 00:08:33.270
but we did visit 100 businesses.

00:08:33.270 --> 00:08:36.260
I traveled around the district
asking local business owners

00:08:36.260 --> 00:08:38.720
about their interests,
their goals, and, you know,

00:08:38.720 --> 00:08:40.020
what kept them up at night.

00:08:40.020 --> 00:08:43.700
And at the of the tour I
could have just listed the 100

00:08:43.700 --> 00:08:45.000
companies I met with

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:47.310
and provided a short
description of each visit.

00:08:47.310 --> 00:08:50.310
I could have written an op ed or
a newsletter announcing the end

00:08:50.310 --> 00:08:53.070
of my tour and then
declaring my findings.

00:08:53.070 --> 00:08:56.840
But instead, my staff
used GIS software

00:08:56.840 --> 00:09:00.740
to build an interactive
map of all the businesses

00:09:00.740 --> 00:09:04.940
that I had visited, accompanied
by pictures of my visits.

00:09:04.940 --> 00:09:08.270
The simple image of a map
of our district dotted

00:09:08.270 --> 00:09:13.650
with 100 flags representing my
stops sent an important message

00:09:13.650 --> 00:09:16.570
that I was committed to
supporting local businesses

00:09:16.570 --> 00:09:19.660
and to promote the growth
of our local economy.

00:09:19.660 --> 00:09:25.120
Now, this is just one way that
GIS has helped me better serve

00:09:25.120 --> 00:09:28.490
and communicate with
my constituents.

00:09:28.490 --> 00:09:33.110
The software is helpful not just
in mapping the places I've been

00:09:33.110 --> 00:09:36.270
but mapping where my
constituents are as well.

00:09:36.270 --> 00:09:39.340
But as the vice-ranking
member of the House Committee

00:09:39.340 --> 00:09:42.910
on Veterans Affairs, ensuring
our veterans get the care

00:09:42.910 --> 00:09:45.930
and support they have earned
is one of my top priorities.

00:09:45.930 --> 00:09:48.680
And it's one of the most
important issues in my district,

00:09:48.680 --> 00:09:52.140
which has a large
veterans population.

00:09:52.140 --> 00:09:56.090
My office can use
mapping technology to find

00:09:56.090 --> 00:10:00.140
out where the veterans in my
district are clustered so that

00:10:00.140 --> 00:10:04.980
when I host a veteran's event,
I know where it should be held.

00:10:04.980 --> 00:10:07.310
We can use it to understand
where veterans live in relation

00:10:07.310 --> 00:10:09.010
to their local VA
healthcare facility

00:10:09.010 --> 00:10:12.520
so we can recognize issues
related to access to care

00:10:12.520 --> 00:10:17.570
and the logistical challenge of
getting to and from facilities.

00:10:17.570 --> 00:10:20.290
We can also use it to appreciate
the geographic distribution

00:10:20.290 --> 00:10:24.120
of veterans by gender,
by age, and by income

00:10:24.120 --> 00:10:26.910
so that we can target
local services to the areas

00:10:26.910 --> 00:10:28.990
that need it the most.

00:10:28.990 --> 00:10:31.180
Where should we host roundtables

00:10:31.180 --> 00:10:33.730
to connect veterans
with local resources?

00:10:33.730 --> 00:10:37.030
Where should a new VA
healthcare facility be built

00:10:37.030 --> 00:10:40.030
to increase access to care?

00:10:40.030 --> 00:10:42.710
Which areas in the community
have the greatest risk

00:10:42.710 --> 00:10:44.980
of veteran homelessness?

00:10:44.980 --> 00:10:48.340
These are all questions that
mapping software can answer.

00:10:48.340 --> 00:10:51.470
So, you know, I'm
going to depart

00:10:51.470 --> 00:10:53.620
from my script a little bit,

00:10:53.620 --> 00:10:57.300
right now in the Congress
we are considering a bill.

00:10:57.300 --> 00:11:00.920
It's called the Air
Act, which would be sort

00:11:00.920 --> 00:11:05.900
of like a [inaudible] for
underutilized VA facilities.

00:11:05.900 --> 00:11:09.660
But one thing I would like
to see is a clear map showing

00:11:09.660 --> 00:11:12.930
where those facilities are
-- all the facilities are,

00:11:12.930 --> 00:11:16.270
whether they're in red
states, blue states, rural.

00:11:16.270 --> 00:11:21.710
I'd like to know -- you know,
we have data from Medicare

00:11:21.710 --> 00:11:26.610
that can tell us about the
quality of care provided

00:11:26.610 --> 00:11:28.690
by the private sector
facilities --

00:11:28.690 --> 00:11:34.940
that should be data that we can
map against all the data VA has

00:11:34.940 --> 00:11:36.240
about its own healthcare.

00:11:36.240 --> 00:11:37.920
I mean, the government's
rich with data.

00:11:37.920 --> 00:11:40.850
And one of the things that
we are, in my opinion,

00:11:40.850 --> 00:11:44.310
is we are pretty transparent
if we have the data.

00:11:44.310 --> 00:11:47.110
How is it we're going
to use that data?

00:11:47.110 --> 00:11:50.920
That would be enormously
useful in a very current issue

00:11:50.920 --> 00:11:54.960
that we have going on and might
even help us get through some

00:11:54.960 --> 00:11:57.750
of the partisan differences.

00:11:57.750 --> 00:12:00.160
I'll speak more about
that in a moment.

00:12:00.160 --> 00:12:04.390
So we live in a society and an
economy that's driven by data.

00:12:04.390 --> 00:12:06.190
Decisions about commerce,
traffic patterns,

00:12:06.190 --> 00:12:08.840
and even baseball strategy
are increasingly using --

00:12:08.840 --> 00:12:13.780
made by using data that did not
exist even a few decades ago.

00:12:13.780 --> 00:12:16.280
Our systems learn and
evolve to fit our needs.

00:12:16.280 --> 00:12:18.440
The Internet knows
my preferences

00:12:18.440 --> 00:12:21.240
and my hobbies better than
some of my own family members.

00:12:21.240 --> 00:12:23.920
And I'm not sure --
and I'm also sure

00:12:23.920 --> 00:12:26.360
that I'm not alone
in that regard.

00:12:26.360 --> 00:12:28.920
Yet when it comes to
policy-making in Congress,

00:12:28.920 --> 00:12:33.790
that type of data-driven
thinking is almost non-existent.

00:12:33.790 --> 00:12:35.190
Anecdotes, partisanship,

00:12:35.190 --> 00:12:38.670
and ideology are filling
the void where data belongs.

00:12:38.670 --> 00:12:41.490
And we're always
experiencing the consequences

00:12:41.490 --> 00:12:44.630
of not using data.

00:12:44.630 --> 00:12:47.800
Programs like GIS can help us
remove the partisan blinders

00:12:47.800 --> 00:12:50.010
and see our challenges
for what they are instead

00:12:50.010 --> 00:12:51.500
of what we want them to be.

00:12:51.500 --> 00:12:53.600
Let me give one more example.

00:12:53.600 --> 00:12:55.580
The common perception
of public transportation

00:12:55.580 --> 00:13:00.950
in Southern California is
to put it kindly not great.

00:13:00.950 --> 00:13:04.750
Because of that, the first
thing people they need to live

00:13:04.750 --> 00:13:08.900
in my region -- that people
think they need in order to live

00:13:08.900 --> 00:13:11.850
in my region is a car.

00:13:11.850 --> 00:13:15.790
And because of that, public
officials are hesitant to invest

00:13:15.790 --> 00:13:18.090
in a public transportation
system

00:13:18.090 --> 00:13:21.310
that many folks will
not even consider using.

00:13:21.310 --> 00:13:22.750
Now, my office built a map

00:13:22.750 --> 00:13:26.020
of public transportation
in the district.

00:13:26.020 --> 00:13:28.560
We found that most neighborhoods
in my community are actually

00:13:28.560 --> 00:13:30.830
within walking distance
of a bus stop.

00:13:30.830 --> 00:13:33.240
And we found that by
adding a few more routes

00:13:33.240 --> 00:13:36.700
in specific areas, the public
transportation system would be

00:13:36.700 --> 00:13:38.200
even more accessible

00:13:38.200 --> 00:13:40.410
for a greater number
of my constituents.

00:13:40.410 --> 00:13:43.780
Now, these small but important
insights are the difference

00:13:43.780 --> 00:13:48.820
between lazy anecdotal thinking
that keeps us stuck in the past

00:13:48.820 --> 00:13:50.870
and focused data-driven thinking

00:13:50.870 --> 00:13:53.640
that can help us
redefine our future.

00:13:53.640 --> 00:13:56.020
Now, these are the insights
that can change the way we think

00:13:56.020 --> 00:14:00.110
of our neighborhoods, our
cities, and our country

00:14:00.110 --> 00:14:02.180
and really can help
us make policies

00:14:02.180 --> 00:14:05.130
that improve the
lives of our citizens.

00:14:05.130 --> 00:14:08.360
GIS software and programs like
it put the power of imagery

00:14:08.360 --> 00:14:11.770
to communicate complex
ideas and the power of data

00:14:11.770 --> 00:14:15.860
to transcend our existing
biases into the hands

00:14:15.860 --> 00:14:18.160
of members of Congress.

00:14:18.160 --> 00:14:20.970
Now, my office continues
to provide trainings

00:14:20.970 --> 00:14:24.300
and step-by-step instructions
for other offices so that more

00:14:24.300 --> 00:14:26.710
of my colleagues can
use the software.

