00:15:58.050 --> 00:15:59.850
&gt;&gt; Mary Mazanec: Good
morning, everyone.

00:15:59.850 --> 00:16:04.730
I am very pleased to be here
today to celebrate GIS Day

00:16:04.730 --> 00:16:06.940
at the Library of Congress.

00:16:06.940 --> 00:16:09.230
Now, as most of you know,

00:16:09.230 --> 00:16:12.680
the Congressional Research
Service works exclusively

00:16:12.680 --> 00:16:14.480
for the Congress.

00:16:14.480 --> 00:16:19.340
And we have been doing
so for over a century.

00:16:19.340 --> 00:16:24.170
As you may know, we provide
both legal and policy analysis

00:16:24.170 --> 00:16:27.120
on all legislative
issues to committees

00:16:27.120 --> 00:16:29.830
and members and their staff.

00:16:29.830 --> 00:16:35.430
And our core values -- our work
is guided by our core values,

00:16:35.430 --> 00:16:39.100
which are authoritativeness,
confidentiality,

00:16:39.100 --> 00:16:42.690
objectivity, and
non-partisanship.

00:16:42.690 --> 00:16:45.140
What you probably don't know is

00:16:45.140 --> 00:16:50.940
that we have been using GIS
technology for over 20 years.

00:16:50.940 --> 00:16:55.950
GIS technology has
advanced significantly

00:16:55.950 --> 00:16:59.150
in the course of
the last 20 years.

00:16:59.150 --> 00:17:05.470
And likewise, our use of GIS in
CRS -- GIS in CRS [Laughs] --

00:17:05.470 --> 00:17:10.220
has also evolved significantly.

00:17:10.220 --> 00:17:16.190
We have moved from using
it ad hoc for an individual

00:17:16.190 --> 00:17:18.320
on a desktop computer

00:17:18.320 --> 00:17:24.230
to actually establishing a GIS
service, which supports all

00:17:24.230 --> 00:17:27.860
of our analysts, attorneys,
and information professionals

00:17:27.860 --> 00:17:30.840
as we do our work for Congress.

00:17:30.840 --> 00:17:35.040
And as many of you in the
audience can appreciate,

00:17:35.040 --> 00:17:40.460
public policy as laid out
by the Congressmen exists

00:17:40.460 --> 00:17:44.160
within geographical boundaries.

00:17:44.160 --> 00:17:51.240
And this makes GIS a wonderful,
fabulous tool that can be used

00:17:51.240 --> 00:17:55.830
to effectively and
succinctly visualize

00:17:55.830 --> 00:18:02.340
and communicate public policy
analysis and very complex ideas.

00:18:02.340 --> 00:18:07.170
Now, I'd like to say that the
hallmark of our GIS team in CRS

00:18:07.170 --> 00:18:10.270
and the way we do our
work is collaboration --

00:18:10.270 --> 00:18:13.210
collaboration with those
of you in the Library

00:18:13.210 --> 00:18:21.090
that are also using GIS and also
to our colleagues on the Hill.

00:18:21.090 --> 00:18:24.380
It is a collaborative
partnership.

00:18:24.380 --> 00:18:30.240
And from the CRS staff, our
team includes GIS analysts,

00:18:30.240 --> 00:18:34.930
research librarians, policy
analysts, and graphic designers.

00:18:34.930 --> 00:18:38.960
And we all work together to try
to produce the most informative

00:18:38.960 --> 00:18:41.580
and best product
for the Congress.

00:18:41.580 --> 00:18:44.250
So I'm going to stop here
and really turn the program

00:18:44.250 --> 00:18:47.790
over to the CRS experts,
if you can join me,

00:18:47.790 --> 00:18:52.270
who will tell you more
specifics about how we use GIS

00:18:52.270 --> 00:18:53.800
to support the Congress.

00:18:53.800 --> 00:18:55.600
Thank you.

