00:19:01.630 --> 00:19:02.930
&gt;&gt; Calvin DeSouza:
Hello, everyone.

00:19:02.930 --> 00:19:04.930
I'm Calvin DeSouza, and I'm
going to talk about GIS,

00:19:04.930 --> 00:19:06.740
along with Hannah
Fischer, my coworker.

00:19:06.740 --> 00:19:09.740
So to reiterate some of
the things that Mary said,

00:19:09.740 --> 00:19:14.000
here at CRS, whenever we work
on a GIS request, we always want

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:16.790
to make sure that we find
the most authoritative data

00:19:16.790 --> 00:19:18.440
that we can possible.

00:19:18.440 --> 00:19:21.560
So when we do that, we pair up
with a librarian or an analyst

00:19:21.560 --> 00:19:24.190
to start working on a topic,
which can range from any

00:19:24.190 --> 00:19:26.510
of these topics that you
see here on the map --

00:19:26.510 --> 00:19:27.810
not a map, on the screen.

00:19:27.810 --> 00:19:29.930
So whenever we work with
a product, we then --

00:19:29.930 --> 00:19:31.230
and finish it, we then take

00:19:31.230 --> 00:19:33.100
to through a multi-separate
view process

00:19:33.100 --> 00:19:34.740
where the results
can be anywhere

00:19:34.740 --> 00:19:38.510
from a confidential memo to
Congressional staff or report,

00:19:38.510 --> 00:19:41.590
or other products, or
in-person briefing, or an email,

00:19:41.590 --> 00:19:47.110
sort of telephone
correspondence back and forth.

00:19:47.110 --> 00:19:49.600
Topics can range from
an international issue.

00:19:49.600 --> 00:19:52.180
So here we have a couple
examples of reference maps

00:19:52.180 --> 00:19:55.300
that we've made for a
couple international issues.

00:19:55.300 --> 00:19:57.080
We work with analysts,
get the appropriate data,

00:19:57.080 --> 00:19:59.180
and we start designing
the map to make sure

00:19:59.180 --> 00:20:00.690
that the appropriate
information is on the map

00:20:00.690 --> 00:20:02.990
to easily convey the
information that we want.

00:20:02.990 --> 00:20:06.830
We can also work on local
issues where we'll reach

00:20:06.830 --> 00:20:08.440
out to the local
governments to try

00:20:08.440 --> 00:20:11.030
to gather what we
need for the maps.

00:20:11.030 --> 00:20:12.630
So it can really
range from anything.

00:20:12.630 --> 00:20:17.330
We're willing to work
with you along the way.

00:20:17.330 --> 00:20:19.030
What are our type of products?

00:20:19.030 --> 00:20:21.360
Sometimes we make maps in
PDF's that we distribute

00:20:21.360 --> 00:20:22.740
to you directly to
Congressional clients.

00:20:22.740 --> 00:20:24.870
Sometimes those same
maps are in reports

00:20:24.870 --> 00:20:28.040
that are along with
other products.

00:20:28.040 --> 00:20:31.150
Sometimes we do GIS analysis
where the result isn't a map,

00:20:31.150 --> 00:20:32.570
it's actually spreadsheet
of data.

00:20:32.570 --> 00:20:35.840
So we've done all this analysis,
and here are the results of it

00:20:35.840 --> 00:20:40.790
in a tabular format that you
can use for other products.

00:20:40.790 --> 00:20:44.260
Some Congressional staff,
they're pretty tech-savvy,

00:20:44.260 --> 00:20:46.980
and now more people with
the GHE, we have access

00:20:46.980 --> 00:20:49.160
to RJS and RJS Online.

00:20:49.160 --> 00:20:51.600
So sometimes some staff want
to do the analysis themselves.

00:20:51.600 --> 00:20:54.290
So they don't know where
to get started with data.

00:20:54.290 --> 00:20:56.780
So we can gather the data
for them, package it up,

00:20:56.780 --> 00:21:00.480
and give it to them so they
can get their analysis started.

00:21:00.480 --> 00:21:03.520
And we're happy to
announce that we're getting

00:21:03.520 --> 00:21:05.280
to the process of
interactive maps.

00:21:05.280 --> 00:21:07.280
So this is a thing that
we're going to start doing,

00:21:07.280 --> 00:21:10.830
including interactive maps
in some of our CRS products.

00:21:10.830 --> 00:21:13.040
And later on the line, we're
going to start find a way

00:21:13.040 --> 00:21:15.090
to do confidential
interactive maps [inaudible].

00:21:15.090 --> 00:21:19.880
So what kind of products
do we have?

00:21:19.880 --> 00:21:21.820
Sometimes we have a
simple reference map --

00:21:21.820 --> 00:21:23.560
what countries are part
of the NATO alliance?

00:21:23.560 --> 00:21:27.130
So we can make a map if
you're traveling to an area

00:21:27.130 --> 00:21:28.660
and you just want to
see this information's,

00:21:28.660 --> 00:21:30.540
what country's a part and
what countries aren't?

00:21:30.540 --> 00:21:34.920
So here's a simple reference
map that we can make.

00:21:34.920 --> 00:21:38.120
Next. We also have
industry-specific research.

00:21:38.120 --> 00:21:40.520
One of the things here at CRS,
the librarians are pretty good

00:21:40.520 --> 00:21:41.820
about searching for information.

00:21:41.820 --> 00:21:45.290
So here's an example of media
outlets in a particular state.

00:21:45.290 --> 00:21:49.070
So can I get a list of all
the newspapers, magazines,

00:21:49.070 --> 00:21:52.510
dailies in my -- say, to
help you with outreach?

00:21:52.510 --> 00:21:55.030
So we can go and get one
of these paper databases,

00:21:55.030 --> 00:21:57.690
digitize it, and then
make a map for it.

00:21:57.690 --> 00:21:58.990
And here is the result.

00:21:58.990 --> 00:22:01.010
So you may not have access

00:22:01.010 --> 00:22:05.220
to this information,
but at CRS, we do.

00:22:05.220 --> 00:22:06.590
One of the great
things that we can do,

00:22:06.590 --> 00:22:09.950
we can help you see how has
legislation changed over time?

00:22:09.950 --> 00:22:13.690
This example we have here,
we have four different areas.

00:22:13.690 --> 00:22:14.990
We have the Nevada test site

00:22:14.990 --> 00:22:16.360
where they were testing
nuclear weapons.

00:22:16.360 --> 00:22:18.000
And there was proposed
legislation

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:19.300
that has change over time.

00:22:19.300 --> 00:22:23.160
The first area was this dash
box, the next where the hash is

00:22:23.160 --> 00:22:25.130
through the counties, and
then the third were the

00:22:25.130 --> 00:22:26.430
yellow counties.

00:22:26.430 --> 00:22:28.360
So you can see there have been
three rounds of legislation.

00:22:28.360 --> 00:22:30.130
How has that changed over time?

00:22:30.130 --> 00:22:32.370
And you can see it on paper,
but sometimes seeing it

00:22:32.370 --> 00:22:35.330
as a picture really
helps you visualize.

00:22:36.410 --> 00:22:39.850
Another example is possible
impacts of legislation.

00:22:39.850 --> 00:22:42.000
Everyone's heard of food
deserts where there's areas

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:45.430
where there are low
access to food.

00:22:45.430 --> 00:22:47.230
But there's no clear definition.

00:22:47.230 --> 00:22:49.200
So there are four definitions
of what a food desert is.

00:22:49.200 --> 00:22:52.280
So if legislations pass, what
definition are they going to use

00:22:52.280 --> 00:22:54.600
and how will that
affect the constituents?

00:22:54.600 --> 00:22:57.090
So we will provide that to
you -- all four examples --

00:22:57.090 --> 00:23:01.040
so you can see which way your
constituents would be affected.

00:23:01.040 --> 00:23:05.720
Another thing we can do, we
can map areas of interest.

00:23:05.720 --> 00:23:10.660
So here is our participation
-- precipitation --

00:23:10.660 --> 00:23:14.600
participation of
the federal program.

00:23:14.600 --> 00:23:16.060
So we can map them up by county,

00:23:16.060 --> 00:23:18.660
by congressional
districts, by state.

00:23:18.660 --> 00:23:20.980
So you can say here's a
Social Security distribution

00:23:20.980 --> 00:23:22.410
by county throughout
United States.

00:23:22.410 --> 00:23:25.080
And then we can also give
you a state-specific map

00:23:25.080 --> 00:23:27.210
so you can compare your
state to other states

00:23:27.210 --> 00:23:30.030
in the products that
we give to you.

00:23:30.030 --> 00:23:32.520
This was mentioned earlier,
mapping constituents;

00:23:32.520 --> 00:23:35.230
where do we have high veteran
populations in our states?

00:23:35.230 --> 00:23:37.550
So it's a simple question,
but it's these sort of things

00:23:37.550 --> 00:23:38.850
that we can provide to you.

00:23:38.850 --> 00:23:40.330
So you can see instead of
this county, this county,

00:23:40.330 --> 00:23:42.390
you can now start
seeing the clusters

00:23:42.390 --> 00:23:44.970
of where we have
high populations

00:23:44.970 --> 00:23:48.990
of whatever our target group
is that we're looking at.

00:23:48.990 --> 00:23:52.120
So next I'm going to
turn the presentation

00:23:52.120 --> 00:23:53.420
to my coworker, Hannah.

00:23:53.420 --> 00:23:56.700
&gt;&gt; Hannah Fischer: Oh,
thank you so much, Calvin.

00:23:56.700 --> 00:24:01.370
Okay. So now I'm going
to give an example

00:24:01.370 --> 00:24:07.780
of how we combine the subject
area expertise that our analysts

00:24:07.780 --> 00:24:11.730
and librarians have here at the
Congressional Research Service

00:24:11.730 --> 00:24:15.200
and how we put that
together with GIS

00:24:15.200 --> 00:24:20.940
to evaluate data sources
and to create GIS products

00:24:20.940 --> 00:24:24.080
that are authoritative
and visually compelling

00:24:24.080 --> 00:24:28.170
and that help Congress
navigate exactly those kinds

00:24:28.170 --> 00:24:30.990
of really complex policy issues

00:24:30.990 --> 00:24:33.610
that Representative
Takano mentioned.

00:24:33.610 --> 00:24:36.660
So let's go ahead
and get started.

00:24:36.660 --> 00:24:42.080
Oh, nope. What were you doing?

00:24:42.080 --> 00:24:43.380
You were just --

00:24:43.380 --> 00:24:44.680
&gt;&gt; Calvin DeSouza: Next.

00:24:44.680 --> 00:24:45.980
&gt;&gt; Hannah Fischer: Next?

00:24:45.980 --> 00:24:47.400
Oh. There we go.

00:24:47.400 --> 00:24:49.140
All right.

00:24:49.140 --> 00:24:53.720
So I'm one member
of the CRS GIS team.

00:24:53.720 --> 00:24:59.200
And I happen to be working
with an analyst here

00:24:59.200 --> 00:25:01.570
who works on refugee issues.

00:25:01.570 --> 00:25:08.810
And she wanted to map all
of the migrants who had died

00:25:08.810 --> 00:25:13.040
in the course of
their migration.

00:25:13.040 --> 00:25:18.180
So she pointed me to a data
source that you can see here,

00:25:18.180 --> 00:25:20.870
the Missing Migrants Project.

00:25:20.870 --> 00:25:26.420
And as you can see, this is a
snapshot from their website.

00:25:26.420 --> 00:25:30.150
And they have it kind of
centered on the Mediterranean.

00:25:30.150 --> 00:25:31.770
And it's very detailed data.

00:25:31.770 --> 00:25:37.250
It looks like a latitude
and longitude

00:25:37.250 --> 00:25:39.960
for every migrant death.

00:25:39.960 --> 00:25:44.590
And so I said, "All right,
let's go ahead and bring

00:25:44.590 --> 00:25:47.840
that into our GIS and
take a look at it."

00:25:47.840 --> 00:25:53.160
So we brought it in, and the
first thing we did was what we

00:25:53.160 --> 00:25:56.510
know every member of Congress
is immediately going to do,

00:25:56.510 --> 00:26:00.390
which is we went to go
look at the United States.

00:26:00.390 --> 00:26:04.180
And when we did that,
we saw that there seemed

00:26:04.180 --> 00:26:10.080
to be these two big
circles that are close to --

00:26:10.080 --> 00:26:15.860
not exactly on but close
to the US/Mexico border.

00:26:15.860 --> 00:26:19.460
And that -- that seemed
a little odd to us.

00:26:19.460 --> 00:26:20.760
So we said, "All right.

00:26:20.760 --> 00:26:23.260
Well, let's take a
closer look at that."

00:26:23.260 --> 00:26:27.750
So we did a little heat
mapping and clicked directly

00:26:27.750 --> 00:26:30.270
on the center of the heat map.

00:26:30.270 --> 00:26:35.040
And it said, "Well,
there's 145 migrant deaths

00:26:35.040 --> 00:26:37.290
at this exact location,

00:26:37.290 --> 00:26:40.640
this particular longitude
and latitude."

00:26:40.640 --> 00:26:47.230
And we thought, "Well, that
just seem very unlikely to us.

00:26:47.230 --> 00:26:50.110
Let's look into that
a little bit more."

00:26:50.110 --> 00:26:54.250
So we went to look at
the data's methodology.

00:26:54.250 --> 00:26:56.960
And indeed, once
which started reading,

00:26:56.960 --> 00:26:59.880
they do address that
exact thing.

00:26:59.880 --> 00:27:01.710
They have this sentence
in there:

00:27:01.710 --> 00:27:05.050
Data on the US/Mexico border
are compiled based on data

00:27:05.050 --> 00:27:07.110
from the US county
medical examiner's

00:27:07.110 --> 00:27:08.410
and sheriff's offices.

00:27:08.410 --> 00:27:13.810
So essentially, data in this
area is collected differently

00:27:13.810 --> 00:27:17.530
than in the rest of the world.

00:27:17.530 --> 00:27:23.620
They roll it up into these
county medical examiner's

00:27:23.620 --> 00:27:29.590
offices for this area, which
is different than the data --

00:27:29.590 --> 00:27:32.860
excuse me -- in the
rest of the world.

00:27:32.860 --> 00:27:41.120
Huh. So I remember
working with the analyst --

00:27:41.120 --> 00:27:44.600
[inaudible] is the analyst, and
then our graphic specialist,

00:27:44.600 --> 00:27:49.080
Amber Wilhelm, who I
see is also in the room.

00:27:49.080 --> 00:27:55.050
And all kind of -- we sat
for a moment and thought

00:27:55.050 --> 00:27:56.910
about this and said, "All right.

00:27:56.910 --> 00:28:00.670
Well, let's go home,
sleep on it,

00:28:00.670 --> 00:28:04.430
and we'll come back tomorrow
and we'll try again."

00:28:04.430 --> 00:28:08.380
So then the next day we came
back and we thought, "All right,

00:28:08.380 --> 00:28:12.240
well, maybe what we can
do is we can explain this.

00:28:12.240 --> 00:28:18.100
We'll come up with some
kind of legend and explain

00:28:18.100 --> 00:28:19.830
that this is a little
bit different

00:28:19.830 --> 00:28:21.130
on the US/Mexico border."

00:28:21.130 --> 00:28:25.670
So here are some
designed legends that kind

00:28:25.670 --> 00:28:27.740
of explain this difference.

00:28:27.740 --> 00:28:31.460
And then we looked at
that for a little while.

00:28:31.460 --> 00:28:34.670
And then we thought,
"Hmm, you know what?

00:28:34.670 --> 00:28:38.310
I think this data, it just --

00:28:38.310 --> 00:28:43.270
right now it doesn't
meet the CRS standards."

00:28:43.270 --> 00:28:47.920
We take very seriously the idea

00:28:47.920 --> 00:28:51.850
that Congress could
make policy based

00:28:51.850 --> 00:28:55.030
on the information
that we give them.

00:28:55.030 --> 00:29:00.570
And the map as it currently is
could potentially be misleading.

00:29:00.570 --> 00:29:05.860
If you didn't go and take a look
and really read the legend here,

00:29:05.860 --> 00:29:07.930
you could kind of
get the wrong idea.

